T1  - Distortion-triggered lobbying and welfare: A contribution to the theory of directly-unproductive profit-seeking activities
AU  - Anam, Mahmudul
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 13
IS  - 1
SP  - 15
EP  - 32
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/08/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(82)90003-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199682900034
AB  - The paper considers the normative implications of lobbying (for non-exclusive income), generated by an exogenously-specified policy intervention. Such lobbying activities are a subset of what Bhagwati has termed directly-unproductive profit-seeking (DUP) activities. It is demonstrated that the welfare effects of lobbying, triggered by a policy distortion, depend critically on whether the direct impact of the policy constraint is on price or an quantity. It is also shown that several standard comparative-static welfare analyses of alternative policy-distorted states are significantly affected once the policy intervention is assumed to be continuously accompanied by lobbying for the associated non-exclusive income.
ER  - 

