AB  - Suppose that a small country is totally dependent upon its trading partners for an essential raw material, the price of which is rising exponentially. Such a country will progressively substitute capital for the raw material. Can such a strategy succeed in the sense of making possible evergrowing per capita consumption? It is shown that in a Cobb-Douglas economy it is necessary and sufficient for success that technical progress accrues at a sufficiently rapid rate, the required rate depending on the rate of growth of consumption.
