DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(82)90005-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199682900058
AB  - The analysis extends and corrects the results of an earlier paper by Hamada. Two problems are analyzed, (1) How is location of production affected by opening up of a free zone taking into account different kinds of trade barriers and zones? Implications for production, consumption and welfare in a number of different cases are analyzed. (2) What are the effects of capital inflow either into the zone or into the host country? Our results show that both types of capital inflow diminish welfare, and welfare diminishes comparatively more when imported into the zone. Repatriated income, as well as its composition, is explicitly incorporated.
